{"title_page": "1952 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1952\n| team = Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| conference = Ohio Valley Conference\n| short_conf = OVC\n| record = 9\u20131\n| conf_record = 4\u20131\n| head_coach = [[Jack Clayton (American football)|Jack Clayton]]\n| hc_year = 5th\n| off_scheme =  \n| def_scheme = \n| stadium = \n| champion = OVC co-champion<br>Refrigerator Bowl champion\n| bowl = [[Refrigerator Bowl]] \n| bowl_result = W 34\u201319 vs. [[Arkansas State Red Wolves football|Arkansas State]]\n}}\n{{1952 Ohio Valley Conference football standings}}\nThe '''1952 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky State College]] in the [[1952 college football season]].  They were coached by [[Jack Clayton (American football)|Jack Clayton]] and shared their first [[List of Ohio Valley Conference football champions|Ohio Valley Conference]] football championship as well as winning their first bowl game, the [[Refrigerator Bowl]].  The team was led by college division AP All-American and All-OVC Quarterback [[Jimmy Feix]] and matched the school record for most wins set in [[1922 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team|1922]].  R.E. Simpson, Marvin Satterly, Gene McFadden, and Max Stevens were also named to the All-OVC team.  Will Price and Willie Watson were team captains.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\nSeptember 20, ''Middle Tennessee'' '''Won''' 33-19 <br>\nSeptember 27, at Evansville '''Won''' 39-0 <br>\nOctober 11, at ''Morehead State'' '''Won''' 39-7 <br>\nOctober 18, Louisiana-Monroe '''Won''' 42-27 <br>\nOctober 25, at ''Tennessee Tech'' '''Lost''' 13-21 <br>\nNovember 1, Delta State '''Won''' 35-13 <br>\nNovember 8, ''Eastern Kentucky'' '''Won''' 48-6 <small>(Homecoming)</small><br>\nNovember 15, Southeast Missouri '''Won''' 41-0 <br>\nNovember 22, at ''Murray State'' '''Won''' 12-7 <br>\n<small>''Italic''  Ohio Valley Conference Game</small><br><br>\n'''Refrigerator Bowl, Evansville, Ind.''' <br>\nDecember 7, vs. Arkansas State '''Won''' 34-19 <br>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n{{Ohio Valley Conference football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1952 Ohio Valley Conference football season|Western Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football seasons]]\n[[Category:Ohio Valley Conference football champion seasons]]\n[[Category:1952 in sports in Kentucky|Western Kentucky football]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1952\n| team = Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| conference = Ohio Valley Conference\n| short_conf = OVC\n| record = 9\u20131\n| conf_record = 4\u20131\n| head_coach = [[Jack Clayton (American football)|Jack Clayton]]\n| hc_year = 5th\n| off_scheme =  \n| def_scheme = \n| stadium = \n| champion = OVC co-champion<br>Refrigerator Bowl champion\n| bowl = [[Refrigerator Bowl]] \n| bowl_result = W 34\u201319 vs. [[Arkansas State Red Wolves football|Arkansas State]]\n}}\n{{1952 Ohio Valley Conference football standings}}\nThe '''1952 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky State College]] in the [[1952 college football season]].  They were coached by [[Jack Clayton (American football)|Jack Clayton]] and shared their first [[List of Ohio Valley Conference football champions|Ohio Valley Conference]] football championship as well as winning their first bowl game, the [[Refrigerator Bowl]].  The team was led by college division AP All-American and All-OVC Quarterback [[Jimmy Feix]] and matched the school record for most wins set in [[1922 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team|1922]].  R.E. Simpson, Marvin Satterly, Gene McFadden, and Max Stevens were also named to the All-OVC team.  Will Price and Willie Watson were team captains.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\nSeptember 20, <i>Middle Tennessee</i> <b>Won</b> 33-19 <br>\nSeptember 27, at Evansville <b>Won</b> 39-0 <br>\nOctober 11, at <i>Morehead State</i> <b>Won</b> 39-7 <br>\nOctober 18, Louisiana-Monroe <b>Won</b> 42-27 <br>\nOctober 25, at <i>Tennessee Tech</i> <b>Lost</b> 13-21 <br>\nNovember 1, Delta State <b>Won</b> 35-13 <br>\nNovember 8, <i>Eastern Kentucky</i> <b>Won</b> 48-6 <small>(Homecoming)</small><br>\nNovember 15, Southeast Missouri <b>Won</b> 41-0 <br>\nNovember 22, at <i>Murray State</i> <b>Won</b> 12-7 <br>\n<small><i>Italic</i>  Ohio Valley Conference Game</small><br><br>\n<b>Refrigerator Bowl, Evansville, Ind.</b> <br>\nDecember 7, vs. Arkansas State <b>Won</b> 34-19 <br>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n{{Ohio Valley Conference football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1952 Ohio Valley Conference football season|Western Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football seasons]]\n[[Category:Ohio Valley Conference football champion seasons]]\n[[Category:1952 in sports in Kentucky|Western Kentucky football]]\n", "name_user": "BEANS X2", "label": "safe", "comment": "WP:WCWproject (HTML text style element <b> (bold) - HTML text style element <i> (italics))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1952_Western_Kentucky_Hilltoppers_football_team"}
{"title_page": "MV Queenscliff (1992)", "text_new": "{{short description|A double ended roll-on/roll-off vehicle ferry}}\n{{other ships|MV Queenscliff}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Searoad Ferry 'Queenscliff', Queenscliff, jjron, 06.07.2010.jpg\n|Ship caption=MV ''Queenscliff'' docking at [[Queenscliff, Victoria|Queenscliff]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=MV ''Queenscliff''<ref name=\"searoad\">{{cite web |url=http://www.searoad.com.au/the-journey/our-vessels/ |title=Searoad - The Vessels |accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship operator=Peninsula Searoad Transport Pty Ltd\n|Ship registry={{AUS}}\n|Ship route=[[Queenscliff, Victoria|Queenscliff]] and [[Sorrento]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship completed=1992\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=22 December 1993\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|9074171}}<ref>[http://www.miramarshipindex.org.nz/ship/list?search_op=*OR&IDNo=*9074171 Miramar] and [http://www.shipspotting.com/search.php?query=*9074171&action=*results Shipspotting]</ref>\n* [[Maritime Mobile Service Identity|MMSI]] Number: 503320400\n* Callsign: VHS2977\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=Double-ended, [[roll-on/roll-off]] catamaran\n|Ship tonnage={{GT|3,200}} (approx)\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|60.1|m|ft|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|16.4|m|ft|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"searoad\"/>\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft={{convert|2.3|m|ft|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship power=Diesel\n|Ship propulsion=2 x 800 kW\n|Ship speed={{convert|11|kn|km/h|0|lk=in}}\n|Ship capacity=*700 passengers\n* 80 cars\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''MV ''Queenscliff''''' is a double ended [[roll-on/roll-off]] vehicle [[ferry]] owned by [[Peninsula Searoad Transport]] of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]. It has operated between the heads of [[Port Phillip|Port Phillip Bay]] between the towns of [[Queenscliff, Victoria|Queenscliff]] and [[Sorrento, Victoria|Sorrento]] since December 1993.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dpc.vic.gov.au/domino/Web_Notes/pressrel.nsf/0cc988f35cba63df4a25620d002c68f3/ce757a23163f570f4a2561f100330b39!OpenDocument&Click= |work=Media Release |publisher=Office of the Premier |title=Premier Launches New Bay Ferry Service |date=22 December 1993 |accessdate=26 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930223526/http://www.dpc.vic.gov.au/domino/Web_Notes/pressrel.nsf/0cc988f35cba63df4a25620d002c68f3/ce757a23163f570f4a2561f100330b39%21OpenDocument%26Click%3D |archivedate=30 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The ferry replaced the earlier ''[[Peninsula Princess (Australia)|Peninsula Princess]]'' used on the route, and can carry approximately 80 vehicles and 700 passengers.<ref name=\"searoad\"/> During the 2011 off season the ferry underwent a $2 Million refit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.intown.com.au/locals/queenscliff/queenscliff-sorrento-ferry.htm |title=Queenscliff Sorrento Ferry |accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Loading and unloading==\nThe MV ''Queenscliff'' is fitted with ramps at the bow and stern of the ship to allow vehicles to roll on at the start of the voyage and roll off at the end of the voyage. This results in a fast turnaround time, with all vehicles and passengers embarking and disembarking in approximately 15 to 20 minutes. The loading facilities are also used by the [[MV Sorrento (2001)|MV ''Sorrento'']], the earlier ''Peninsula Princess'' used a different ramp at Queenscliff.\n\nAt Queenscliff, the ship docks bow into the terminal. The bow of the ship consists of two sections; one section raises whilst the other lowers forming a ramp that allows vehicles to drive off. Once all vehicles and foot passengers have disembarked the ship, vehicles travelling to Sorrento then board and face the stern of the ship for the voyage. At Sorrento, the ship docks stern into the terminal. A ramp at the stern of the ship lowers allowing vehicles to drive off. Once all vehicles and foot passengers have disembarked, vehicles travelling to Queenscliff then board and face the bow of the ship for the voyage.\n\nFoot passengers embark and disembark the ship, via the same ramps that vehicles do, under the direction of the ship's crew in between the embarkation and disembarkation of vehicles.\n\n==Gallery==\n{{multiple image\n| footer    =\n| align     = left\n| image1    = The Searoad Queenscliff-Sorrento Ferry 'Queenscliff', rear view leaving Queenscliff, jjron, 06.07.2010.jpg\n| width1    = {{#expr: (200 * 1600 / 1067) round 0}}\n| alt1      = Rear view of the ferry\n| caption1  = Rear view of the ferry\n| image2    = The Searoad Queenscliff-Sorrento Ferry 'MV Queenscliff' Interior, jjron, 05.07.2010.jpg\n| width2    = {{#expr: (200 * 1600 / 1067) round 0}}\n| alt2      = Pre refit interior view of the ferry\n| caption2  = Pre refit interior view of the ferry\n}}\n{{-}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[MV Sorrento (2001)|MV ''Sorrento'']]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|IMO 9074171}}\n* [http://www.searoad.com.au Peninsula Searoad Ferry]\n\n{{Australianferries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Queenscliff}}\n[[Category:Ferries of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Transport in Geelong]]\n[[Category:Transport in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:1992 ships]]\n[[Category:Port Phillip]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A double ended roll-on/roll-off vehicle ferry}}\n{{other ships|MV Queenscliff}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{|{{I